<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06344132 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06344132 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  ELECTRONICS; COMPUTER; COMPANY; STOCK; TRADE  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  IBM Chairman John Akers, meeting with skeptical stock analysts, today outlinedplans for revamping the leading computer maker, saying he intends todramatically raise its performance in the next three years.;   The meetingbetween the head of International Business Machines Corp. and Wall Streetstrategists who follow the company was the first in two years and seemed tosignal IBM management's intent to improve its image on Wall Street.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Business  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  IBM TRIES TO REASSURE A SKEPTICAL WALL STREET  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     IBM's stock hit a 12-year low of $89 on Friday, partly because of investorgloom over how the world's largest manufacturer of computers has beenresponding to the slump in the industry and the global economic slowdown.;  Akers described in more detail the previously announced restructuring, inwhich IBM intends to decentralize to give units more autonomy. He said thecompany intends on gaining market share next year.;   He also said the companyintends to boost its return on equity, a mathematical measure of how valuablethe stock is to investors over time, to 18 percent within three years. IBM'sreturn on equity was about 10 percent in 1989 and about 14 percent last year.;  Analyst Rick Martin of Prudential Securities Inc., said he estimates IBM'sreturn on equity this year will be in a single digit percentage.;   &quot;This is abeginning of a new and evolving IBM company,&quot; Akers said.;   Akers alsorepeated an earlier company assertion that IBM's practice of not laying offworkers &quot;will clearly be on the table&quot; if the company can't improve resultsthrough voluntary severance moves.;   IBM said two weeks ago it wouldeliminate 20,000 jobs through voluntary means next year, on top of the 20,000it is eliminating this year.;   The chairman described good prospects forIBM's mainframes, minicomputers, work stations and high-end personalcomputers, but he said the low-end PC business was hurt by low-cost clonesmade by other manufacturers.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  New York  </CITY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911209  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Monday  </DAY><MONTH>  December  </MONTH><PG.COL>  13D  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  311  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Monday, December 9, 199100344132,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>